[{'created': '2020-09-11 16:32:08.000000000', 'message': "Move revert resize under semaphore

As discussed in change I26b050c402f5721fc490126e9becb643af9279b4, the
resource tracker's periodic task is reliant on the status of migrations
to determine whether to include usage from these migrations in the
total, and races between setting the migration status and decrementing
resource usage via 'drop_move_claim' can result in incorrect usage.
That change tackled the confirm resize operation. This one changes the
revert resize operation, and is a little trickier due to kinks in how
both the same-cell and cross-cell resize revert operations work.

For same-cell resize revert, the 'ComputeManager.revert_resize'
function, running on the destination host, sets the migration status to
'reverted' before dropping the move claim. This exposes the same race
that we previously saw with the confirm resize operation. It then calls
back to 'ComputeManager.finish_revert_resize' on the source host to boot
up the instance itself. This is kind of weird, because, even ignoring
the race, we're marking the migration as 'reverted' before we've done
any of the necessary work on the source host.

The cross-cell resize revert splits dropping of the move claim and
setting of the migration status between the source and destination host
tasks. Specifically, we do cleanup on the destination and drop the move
claim first, via 'ComputeManager.revert_snapshot_based_resize_at_dest'
before resuming the instance and setting the migration status on the
source via
'ComputeManager.finish_revert_snapshot_based_resize_at_source'. This
would appear to avoid the weird quirk of same-cell migration, however,
in typical weird cross-cell fashion, these are actually different
instances and different migration records.

The solution is once again to move the setting of the migration status
and the dropping of the claim under 'COMPUTE_RESOURCE_SEMAPHORE'. This
introduces the weird setting of migration status before completion to
the cross-cell resize case and perpetuates it in the same-cell case, but
this seems like a suitable compromise to avoid attempts to do things
like unplugging already unplugged PCI devices or unpinning already
unpinned CPUs. From an end-user perspective, instance state changes are
what really matter and once a revert is completed on the destination
host and the instance has been marked as having returned to the source
host, hard reboots can help us resolve any remaining issues.

Change-Id: I29d6f4a78c0206385a550967ce244794e71cef6d
Signed-off-by: Stephen Finucane <stephenfin@redhat.com>
Closes-Bug: #1879878
(cherry picked from commit dc9c7a5ebf11253f86127238d33dff7401465155)
"}]
commit_message:
Move revert resize under semaphore

As discussed in change I26b050c402f5721fc490126e9becb643af9279b4, the
resource tracker's periodic task is reliant on the status of migrations
to determine whether to include usage from these migrations in the
total, and races between setting the migration status and decrementing
resource usage via 'drop_move_claim' can result in incorrect usage.
That change tackled the confirm resize operation. This one changes the
revert resize operation, and is a little trickier due to kinks in how
both the same-cell and cross-cell resize revert operations work.

For same-cell resize revert, the 'ComputeManager.revert_resize'
function, running on the destination host, sets the migration status to
'reverted' before dropping the move claim. This exposes the same race
that we previously saw with the confirm resize operation. It then calls
back to 'ComputeManager.finish_revert_resize' on the source host to boot
up the instance itself. This is kind of weird, because, even ignoring
the race, we're marking the migration as 'reverted' before we've done
any of the necessary work on the source host.

The cross-cell resize revert splits dropping of the move claim and
setting of the migration status between the source and destination host
tasks. Specifically, we do cleanup on the destination and drop the move
claim first, via 'ComputeManager.revert_snapshot_based_resize_at_dest'
before resuming the instance and setting the migration status on the
source via
'ComputeManager.finish_revert_snapshot_based_resize_at_source'. This
would appear to avoid the weird quirk of same-cell migration, however,
in typical weird cross-cell fashion, these are actually different
instances and different migration records.

The solution is once again to move the setting of the migration status
and the dropping of the claim under 'COMPUTE_RESOURCE_SEMAPHORE'. This
introduces the weird setting of migration status before completion to
the cross-cell resize case and perpetuates it in the same-cell case, but
this seems like a suitable compromise to avoid attempts to do things
like unplugging already unplugged PCI devices or unpinning already
unpinned CPUs. From an end-user perspective, instance state changes are
what really matter and once a revert is completed on the destination
host and the instance has been marked as having returned to the source
host, hard reboots can help us resolve any remaining issues.

Change-Id: I29d6f4a78c0206385a550967ce244794e71cef6d
Signed-off-by: Stephen Finucane <stephenfin@redhat.com>
Closes-Bug: #1879878
(cherry picked from commit dc9c7a5ebf11253f86127238d33dff7401465155)

commit_message:
Update UPPER_CONSTRAINTS_FILE for stable/stein

Update the URL to the upper-constraints file to point to the redirect
rule on releases.openstack.org so that anyone working on this branch
will switch to the correct upper-constraints list automatically when
the requirements repository branches.

Until the requirements repository has as stable/stein branch, tests will
continue to use the upper-constraints list on master.

Change-Id: Ic3d011876a9920d35ddfec900317d60751064f70

commit_message:
Remove DHCP agent scheduling when subnet created

Historically, there was workaround in DHCP agent scheduling [1]. Now,
provisioning_block assure right order of port activeness so it's good
time to delete workaround

For routed network, we have DHCP agent to be scheduled at creating
subnet since segment has host bindings. Schedule only for the case
using 'candidate_hosts' rather than all subnets.

[1] https://bugs.launchpad.net/neutron/+bug/1431105

Change-Id: I787e02167d0ff690e0ba9c06d7f00f82328e2e2f

[{'created': '2019-11-08 14:08:23.000000000', 'message': 'objects/agent: Remove group_by from agent query

The query select all fields from the table and having a group by in this
case only works on MySQL, but breaks on PostgreSQL with:

ERROR neutron.pecan_wsgi.hooks.translation oslo_db.exception.DBError: (psycopg2.errors.GroupingError) column "agents.id" must appear in the GROUP BY clause or be used in an aggregate function
ERROR neutron.pecan_wsgi.hooks.translation LINE 1: SELECT agents.id AS agents_id, agents.agent_type AS agents_a...

Based on the function's name it shouldn't do any grouping and return all
agents. For the only caller this group by is kind of an optimization,
but the caller also does deduplication, so let's just remove it.

Change-Id: Ibe3034e93d3b6ee3a2b95fbb641f3a80d8e597c0
Signed-off-by: Sven Wegener <sven.wegener@inovex.de>
'}]
commit_message:
objects/agent: Remove group_by from agent query

The query select all fields from the table and having a group by in this
case only works on MySQL, but breaks on PostgreSQL with:

ERROR neutron.pecan_wsgi.hooks.translation oslo_db.exception.DBError: (psycopg2.errors.GroupingError) column "agents.id" must appear in the GROUP BY clause or be used in an aggregate function
ERROR neutron.pecan_wsgi.hooks.translation LINE 1: SELECT agents.id AS agents_id, agents.agent_type AS agents_a...

Based on the function's name it shouldn't do any grouping and return all
agents. For the only caller this group by is kind of an optimization,
but the caller also does deduplication, so let's just remove it.

Change-Id: Ibe3034e93d3b6ee3a2b95fbb641f3a80d8e597c0
Signed-off-by: Sven Wegener <sven.wegener@inovex.de>

commit_message:
Don't advertise reserved DHCP ports as DNS servers

DHCP ports marked 'reserved_dhcp_port' need to be excluded from the list
of nameservers that the DHCP server advertises to a VM. Given that
resolv.conf only uses upto 3 nameservers, it is possible that VMs will
have their name resolution broken if there are more than 3 DHCP ports
marked reserved_dhcp_port. This change excludes these ports from the
list of nameservers advertised to instances.

Change-Id: Ib1fb87874cb9f759883a2aaa3db39c0717dd5472
Closes-Bug: #1852504

Please see my comment to https://bugs.launchpad.net/neutron/+bug/1853632. Also, please check the results of the neutron-tempest-plugin-designate-scenario. All the test cases are broken by this change'}, {'account_id': 30309, 'date': '2019-11-25 11:57:57.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Hi Miguel,

from what I can see in the job logs, the failures seem to be related to my proposed changes.

After a long search I found the following in `controller/logs/screen-q-svc.txt.gz`:

  "ERROR neutron.api.v2.resource oslo_config.cfg.DuplicateOptError: duplicate option: project-name"

This option does seem to already be used by the auth plugin.

Could you point me to that plugin? I do not seem to find it.

Furthermore, we are hitting this issue in Queens, the openstack packages are installed from the RDO Queens CentOS repository, and with these changes we have no issues and can:

 - allocate floating ips
 - have automatically generated dns A and PTR records for newly created instances

Should I submit this proposal to stable/queens branch? or you will eventually merge the changes to the auth plugin?

Am I missing something here?

Cheers!'}, {'account_id': 11975, 'date': '2020-09-25 15:46:49.000000000', 'content': "Abandoned

You changed the file permissions from 644 to 755, please change that back'}, {'account_id': 15554, 'date': '2019-11-26 13:54:07.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 37: Code-Review-1

(1 comment)

As others mentioned it this change is modifying what neutron accepts on its API therefore it must introduce an extension to make this change discoverable to the users of neutron API. You're not adding a new resource (like routers), nor a new resource attribute (likes routes for routers). You're only extending what values are considered valid for router routes, therefore the extension can be a so called 'shim' extension. You can find an example for that here:

https://opendev.org/openstack/neutron-lib/src/commit/85205e9f08dddee9246969fbc66a6ae366ae1946/neutron_lib/api/definitions/project_id.py

Also here's another gerrit topic of changes introducing a new neutron feature which is bit more complex than what you're doing here, but it's still relatively simple so it's probably a good example to follow (for example it also adds api-ref documentation in its neutron-lib part):

https://review.opendev.org/#/q/topic:l3-conntrack-helper"}, {'account_id': 11975, 'date': '2020-09-25 15:46:40.000000000', 'content': "Abandoned

commit_message:
add optional argument metric to set metric for routes

A routing metric is a quantitative value used to evaluate
the path cost. A new optional argument metric can be added
to set the metric for the routes. This value can be set by
the user or have a default value.

DocImpact
Closes-Bug: #1759790
Implements: [RFE] metric for the route

Depends-On: Ic4a16953f3c5b65358c79f3472989fb90edc72a0
Change-Id: I64c26269dd3f00756d0361e16534ac6145706a42

commit_message:
Fix designate driver not being fully region aware

The admin part of the designate implementation, never
passes the region or url to client. This means that it
may fail in multi-region situations.

We fix this by always passing the endpoint
override to the client every-time it's instantiated.

(cherry picked from commit 654c1f06d583965c4b5a2ae721a7b1f3786dc76a)

Adds required auth config
Add support for missing designate configuration options
Adds domain settings to designate external dns driver

Change-Id: Ie00467412d2cbe21e312b260d1d5470442d4dfaf
Closes-Bug: #1853632
Signed-off-by: Manuel Torrinha <manuel.torrinha@tecnico.ulisboa.pt>

commit_message:
Filter ports based on subnet segment IDs

Changed get_network_info() and get_active_networks_info()
to filter ports based on subnet segment IDs.

If we don't, a failure can occur if the DHCP agent is
stopped, namespaces are cleaned-up and the agent restarted,
leading to the tracebacks in the bug.

Change-Id: I47707e63bdde6b71947e19242a4a52ecc4ed3262
Closes-bug: #1849726

revisions:
[{'created': '2019-09-11 12:54:51.000000000', 'message': "Support encapsulated DHCP options

Some PXE implementations, including iPXE, use vendor-specific options
encapsulated in a single top-level option to send configuration data in
DHCP packets. As an example, iPXE encapsulates various options in option
175.

This is fully supported by dnsmasq (see below), however, the original
code which translates a DHCP option name and value into a dnsmasq
command-line argument would expect any non-numeric option 'name' to be a
named option, hence prepending with `option:`.

This change ensures `encap:X,Y` is properly translated into either
`encap:X,Y` if Y is numerical, or `encap:X,option:Y` if Y is text.

From `man 8 dnsmasq`:

```
-O, --dhcp-option=[tag:<tag>,[tag:<tag>,]][encap:<opt>,]
    [vi-encap:<enterprise>,][vendor:[<vendor-class>],]
    [<opt>|option:<opt-name>|option6:<opt>|option6:<opt-name>],
    [<value>[,<value>]]
...
    Options may be encapsulated (IPv4 only) within other options: for
    instance --dhcp-option=encap:175,190,iscsi-client0 will send option
    175, within which is the option 190. If multiple options are given
    which are encapsulated with the same option number then they will be
    correctly combined into one encapsulated option. encap: and vendor:
    are may not both be set in the same --dhcp-option.
...
```

One could argue the code ought to be improved to handle `vi-encap` and
`vendor` options as well...

commit_message:
Support encapsulated DHCP options

Some PXE implementations, including iPXE, use vendor-specific options
encapsulated in a single top-level option to send configuration data in
DHCP packets. As an example, iPXE encapsulates various options in option
175.

This is fully supported by dnsmasq (see below), however, the original
code which translates a DHCP option name and value into a dnsmasq
command-line argument would expect any non-numeric option 'name' to be a
named option, hence prepending with `option:`.

This change ensures `encap:X,Y` is properly translated into either
`encap:X,Y` if Y is numerical, or `encap:X,option:Y` if Y is text.

From `man 8 dnsmasq`:

```
-O, --dhcp-option=[tag:<tag>,[tag:<tag>,]][encap:<opt>,]
    [vi-encap:<enterprise>,][vendor:[<vendor-class>],]
    [<opt>|option:<opt-name>|option6:<opt>|option6:<opt-name>],
    [<value>[,<value>]]
...
    Options may be encapsulated (IPv4 only) within other options: for
    instance --dhcp-option=encap:175,190,iscsi-client0 will send option
    175, within which is the option 190. If multiple options are given
    which are encapsulated with the same option number then they will be
    correctly combined into one encapsulated option. encap: and vendor:
    are may not both be set in the same --dhcp-option.
...
```

One could argue the code ought to be improved to handle `vi-encap` and
`vendor` options as well...

Closes-bug: #1860488
Change-Id: I40f4dc04dd46dddc728cc5432fb3c99049931141

commit_message:
Change ResourceAllocator tests to not use /tmp

/tmp should not be hard-coded in test paths, instead
use get_temp_file_path() to create test-specific
directories that will be automatically cleaned-up.

Change-Id: Ida45d82a000e8126ba40ab6be57dae57d6311297

commit_message:
(PoC)Classification field in Neutron DSCP

This patch is a PoC to demonstrate integration of
Neutron Classifier into Neutron QoS.
Includes, duplication of Rules so long as classifications
group ids don't overlap.

Change-Id: I03133e2213aae07d1e5a47ee845595dad43b638e

commit_message:
Introduction of Neutron Classifier

This patch migrates the neutron classifier service plugin into neutron's
core repo.
Also adds a mixin for the AgentExtensionsAPI to allow extensions to
retrieve the dictionary of a classification group.

- added a temporary file to store exceptions locally in Neutron for gate.

Depends-on: https://review.opendev.org/#/c/670049/
Change-Id: Ifb2610ca08c9e5012e08e2c86bbe3f29d4263e63

commit_message:
[DNM] Enable OVN RBAC by default

__NOTE__ We can currently not enable this in the gate as there
appear to be a couple of optimizations added to the Neutron
OVN mech driver that writes to the OVN Southbound database.

As soon as these have been replaced by fixes in OVN itself we
can remove the writes to the OVN Southbound database from
Neutron and enable RBAC in the gate test.

Change-Id: I69d466226875bbd1ab43eb29de91f7fc1bb9dbce
Related-Bug: #1864640

revisions:
[{'created': '2019-07-10 22:06:56.000000000', 'message': "[WIP] Block non-standard ethertypes by default

This change adds a new capability that works with the iptables_hybrid
firewall to control ethertypes.  The standard ethertypes corresponding
to IPv4, IPv6, and ARP are permitted, as are ethertypes that are
permitted by configuration option.  All other ethertypes are blocked by
default.

This feature will be controlled by a boolean configuration option that
will default to 'false' so that an operator upgrading a cloud without
prior knowledge of this feature will not suddenly find their cloud
applications that make use of custom ethertypes to be broken.  The use
of this feature is highly suggested but not without testing and
validation.

This is a work in progress.  Pending to-do items include but are not
limited to:

- Add the configuration option to enable/disable this feature
- Functional tests
- Release note
- Make sure that this does not interfere with the arp spoofing
protection implementation in the linuxbridge mech driver

Spec for this feature: https://review.opendev.org/#/c/668242/

Change-Id: Icdf083ee279102d30ccb7b19e5299dd1cc743d72
Resolves-Bug: #1832758

commit_message:
[WIP] Block non-standard ethertypes by default

This change adds a new capability that works with the iptables_hybrid
firewall to control ethertypes.  The standard ethertypes corresponding
to IPv4, IPv6, and ARP are permitted, as are ethertypes that are
permitted by configuration option.  All other ethertypes are blocked by
default.

This feature will be controlled by a boolean configuration option that
will default to 'false' so that an operator upgrading a cloud without
prior knowledge of this feature will not suddenly find their cloud
applications that make use of custom ethertypes to be broken.  The use
of this feature is highly suggested but not without testing and
validation.

This is a work in progress.  Pending to-do items include but are not
limited to:

- Make sure that this does not interfere with the arp spoofing
protection implementation in the linuxbridge mech driver
- Ensure that the implementation for OVS firewall is also configured
properly when using this facility.

Spec for this feature: https://review.opendev.org/#/c/668242/

Co-Authored-By: Slawek Kaplonski <skaplons@redhat.com>

Depends-On: https://review.opendev.org/673692
Change-Id: Icdf083ee279102d30ccb7b19e5299dd1cc743d72
Resolves-Bug: #1838473

commit_message:
Fix unnecessary network flap when update FIP

While updating FIP without port or fixed ip changed.
For example, updating its description via neutron API,
or associate same floatingip and fixed ip more than once,
it will delete the old one ,than add a new one[0].
Then,it will make network flap.

Because we don't change FIP or fixed ip , so there is no
need to update NBDB table, and the network flap should be avoided.

[0]https://github.com/openstack/neutron/blob/master/neutron/plugins/ml2/drivers/ovn/mech_driver/ovsdb/ovn_client.py#L1089

Change-Id: I96cf48856df738dbe35854e42162a1ebc65af105
Related-Bug: #1867122

As commented in the LPP bug, I don't know why we need an alias for priority when we can use this word.

Where "pref" is used?'}, {'account_id': 16688, 'date': '2020-03-26 14:24:37.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

> As commented in the LPP bug, I don't know why we need an alias for
 > priority when we can use this word.
 > 
 > Where "pref" is used?

Ok, now I see where in the code "priority" is used [1].

The problem here is that this function, "_make_canonical", is used to set the input parameters and parse the CLI output. Because the priority parameter if "priority" for Neutron and "pref" for ip-rule, we can't make this change.

Instead you should:
- Keep the current code in "_parse_line": there we read the first parameter in the CLI string and assign to "priority"
- Change any ip rule add/modify call input parameter, from "priority" to "pref".

BTW, this change should came with the corresponding functional test.

[1] https://bugs.launchpad.net/neutron/+bug/1869139/comments/6'}, {'account_id': 11975, 'date': '2020-09-25 15:43:39.000000000', 'content': "Abandoned

commit_message:
Convert pref to priority for canonicalization.

In IP rule the pref and priority are interchangeable.When using
pref as input, the returned result is priority, which is not
standard, so need to convert pref to priority every time.

Change-Id: I1f0ce9ae8895836b37d66e6cbf2eeb71277f60fe
Closes-Bug: #1869139

commit_message:
If a network is updated with an MTU too large reject it

We reject MTU values greater than global_physnet_mtu on network create,
we should do the same on network update.

Change-Id: I5eb9596348d5525c3983b76530cd4f252fa95e41
Resolves-bug: 1867214

commit_message:
[WIP] Add segments info to neutron network context

If segments is available, we should add this information
to the neutron context, instead hiding it somewhere.

This would help us skip some unnecessary db fetches.

Depends-On: https://review.opendev.org/#/c/716275

Related-Bug: 1869877

commit_message:
[DNR] Check new engine facade effectiveness

Try enabling the new engine facade in the neutron objects base class to
see if things work well or if there is massive breakage.  When I tested
locally, it was the latter, and I want to have that documented before
talking about it in the PTG.

Change-Id: Ie0ff87732847ea060ee457afba51cfe6ba54088f

> I like this solution. But the pep8 needs to be be fixed.

Darragh O'Reilly, thank for your comments, I did find L3 flood because qrouter used static ARP and couldn't send ARP request, but this fix resulted in L3 performance drop, about 30% per our test, can you help try it and check if the same performance issue is there?

Per our ovs experience, we can't directly output the packets to patch port, the behavior is unknown and uncertain, Yajie needs to change code to output it to vxlan port directly. Per Yulong's patch, it seems that also output the packets to vxlan port but not patch-tun."}, {'account_id': 9531, 'date': '2020-03-31 14:54:58.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

The fix of bug #1732067 has a config option ``explicitly_egress_direct`` [1] which can be used for non-OVS firewall as well.
Please have a try to add the following config option to your compute nodes to see if the flooding still happen:
[agent]
...
explicitly_egress_direct = True

For more details, please see my comment here:
https://bugs.launchpad.net/neutron/+bug/1866445/comments/18'}, {'account_id': 2733, 'date': '2020-03-31 15:18:34.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

@Li YaJie: I tested this and I still see flooding in the east/west routing case. Packets from VMs with dl_dst=gateway_mac hit the NORMAL action in table 60 and are flooded because the gateway_mac is not learned. So it seems we need another flow somewhere to direct these packets to the qr- port.'}, {'account_id': 2733, 'date': '2020-03-31 15:37:18.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

I had explicitly_egress_direct=True. Your patch does not flood after setting it false.'}, {'account_id': 30454, 'date': '2020-04-01 01:04:26.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

> The fix of bug #1732067 has a config option ``explicitly_egress_direct``
 > [1] which can be used for non-OVS firewall as well.
 > Please have a try to add the following config option to your
 > compute nodes to see if the flooding still happen:
 > [agent]
 > ...
 > explicitly_egress_direct = True
 > 
 > For more details, please see my comment here:
 > https://bugs.launchpad.net/neutron/+bug/1866445/comments/18

Yulong, your patch can't work for firewall_driver=iptables_hybrid, I submitted one https://review.opendev.org/#/c/712640/ which can make sure it can work for iptables_hybrid.

I can double confirm your fix patch plus https://review.opendev.org/#/c/712640/ can fix our issue, no L2 and L3 flood.

But I don't understand why your patch doesn't have L3 flood even if you didn't add flows to handle that case. DVR qrouter used static ARP, it won't send ARP request, OVS didn't learn MAC, but it doesn't have L3 flood, can you help explain why."}, {'account_id': 31769, 'date': '2020-04-01 03:07:24.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

@Darragh O'Reilly: thank for your comments. You are right, the flooding still exists when the packets from VMs with dl_dst=gateway_map. This is my mistake, I forgot to deal with this situation, I will fix it."}, {'account_id': 9531, 'date': '2020-04-01 12:19:11.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

commit_message:
Avoid Layer 2 and Layer 3 traffic flooding in DVR mode.

This patch add a new flow table AVOID_FLOOD_TABLE(59) which
process the packets with src_mac is gateway_mac. In order to
avoid l2 flooding, move the original flows to local port in
table 60 to the table 59 and add the gateway_mac in the match.
So the egress and ingress traffic of l2 traffic will always
use the NORMAL flow in table 60 and the mac address of remote
ports will be learned.

For the l3 traffic, this patch add flow in table 0 which
resubmit the packets from router interface to table 59. There
are two kinds of flows in table 59. One is to process the
packets which from the local router to local ports. The other
is a low priority flow to process the packets which sent from
local router to remote ports and the packets sent to patch_tun_port,
so the egress traffic will be directed to the patch_tun_port
and will not to be flood.

Change-Id: I257cc4966379ddacbcaa6fbe8552e638cda303f3
Closes-bug: #1866445

Current code adds all commands to a single transaction for commit.
Sometimes, this will not work if the number of commands are big (>1000).

As these commands are independent, there is no need to do them in one
transaction. Allow the ability to split this up into multiple transactions so a
big sync might be able to progress incrementally.

'}]
commit_message:
WIP: Sync enhancement for big data sets

Current code adds all commands to a single transaction for commit.
Sometimes, this will not work if the number of commands are big (>1000).

As these commands are independent, there is no need to do them in one
transaction. Allow the ability to split this up into multiple transactions so a
big sync might be able to progress incrementally.

Partial-Bug: #1871272
Change-Id: Ie73cfbd6616f79f0b1f3e5e9e1fae3d3a4784ae8

commit_message:
WIP: Replace depreacted filter:healthcheck by app:healthcheck

After applying the same patch on other OpenStack services, it
appears that healthcheck should be an app, not a filter.

This patch:
- Switches to an app, instead of a filter.
- Add the disable_by_file_path plugin.
- Add a functional test to make sure all of this is always working.

Change-Id: I7e4cd88281fb573ca7f91068f1645a474c6be7c3

revisions:
[{'created': '2020-05-09 00:32:44.000000000', 'message': 'Reraise timeout exception

Catch all exceptions during get_device_details would likely cause problems when agent is starting up, because agent is going to clean stale flows eventually.

Ideally cleaning should also depend on values from failed devices but rather than sort out different situations, it might be beneficially to simply failed the sync when MQ is running abnormally.

Change-Id: I780a7d5f9a9c2e23ff421ecaebe6dbfbefc4450a
'}, {'created': '2020-05-11 13:28:37.000000000', 'message': 'Reraise timeout exception

Catch all exceptions in get_device_details would likely
cause problems when agent is starting up. For example,
imagine there are many ports hosted by one ovs-agent, and
unfortunately rabbitmq is working abnormally where consecutive
calls of get_device_detail could fail ocassionaly which means
only partial information is retrieved by agent, and those devices
which do not get fetched will be classed as failed and eventually
they are cleared in flow because they are stale.

We shuould be more careful on clear stable flows by either by

commit_message:
Reraise timeout exception

Catch all exceptions in get_device_details would likely
cause problems when agent is starting up. For example,
imagine there are many ports hosted by one ovs-agent, and
unfortunately rabbitmq is working abnormally where consecutive
calls of get_device_detail could fail ocassionaly which means
only partial information is retrieved by agent, and those devices
which do not get fetched will be classed as failed and eventually
they are cleared in flow because they are stale.

We shuould be more careful on clear stable flows by either by
sorting out different scenarios and figure out coresponding actions.
But for me, maybe it is more consistent by simply raising timeout
exception just like other api did.

Change-Id: I780a7d5f9a9c2e23ff421ecaebe6dbfbefc4450a
Partial-Bug: #1877248

commit_message:
[Fullstack] Refactor SG tests

As firewall driver in fullstack tests can interfere between various
tests, all tests were so far added to single test in the class.

It was hard e.g. to debug when exaclty specific issue happend.
So now, as those tests are always run serially (at least in the gate)
lets refactor it and make separate test cases for various scenarios.

Change-Id: I4b52ebed6ae6fe568a0d725e08fcdb2c819341f2

commit_message:
Ensure iptables rule was added only once

This patch adds a check for iptables_manager to ensure the rule
was added only once to the list. This will avoid some unexpected
behavior during rule removal procedure.

Change-Id: I352b0ff734682dfa8c3f95e938fd8455f720c674
Closes-Bug: #1845145

commit_message:
Enable test_ping_global_ip_from_vm_with_fip in tha gate

The test has been introduced recently to neutron-tempest-plugin [1] but is
disabled by default. This patch makes 8.8.8.8 serve as a public IP that
we try to ping to.

[1] https://review.opendev.org/#/c/727764/

Change-Id: I83226dffefd0451e0c27b1f65f3a8b217fde8d4c

commit_message:
Keep stale flows if there are failed devices

Under some circumstances, some devices may not be
successfully updated and added to failed device map.
Delay stable flow cleaning until failed devices are
gone.

Change-Id: Icef940c6a6619f988460d8544ad646a31fbf7195
Related-Bugs: #1877248

commit_message:
Temporarily disable timeouts for neutron-ovn-db-sync-util

The standard timeouts will almost certainly be hit when dealing
with a database of any significant size. Some timeouts are runtime
config opts, others are stored in the various OVS databases. This
patch will store the existing values, effectively disable the
timeouts, then restore the previous values.

This is a PoC to see if others like this kind of solution, or if
it should be relegated to some kind of deployment tool, so I'd
like some feedback. Thanks!

TODO:
Testing
Make configurable?
Group into transactions for NB/SB DB ops

Change-Id: I53b4113ba90be6a7f415d67ed38c962c1700c3bf

[{'created': '2020-06-10 17:33:55.000000000', 'message': "[WIP] ovn: Implement stateless security groups support

OVN uses 'allow' action for stateless ACLs. This patch makes to use
'allow' for stateless and 'allow-related' actions for stateful security
groups.

Limitation: There is currently an issue in core OVN that makes it not
possible to use statless ACL if a stateful ACL is present for port on
the same chassis.

NOTE: I don't know how to enable stateful-security-group API extension
so unittests are currently failing.

Blueprint: stateless-security-groups

Change-Id: I6f8ad1461cb3059aeb606b936296b8113538896e
Signed-off-by: Jakub Libosvar <libosvar@redhat.com>
"}]
commit_message:
[WIP] ovn: Implement stateless security groups support

OVN uses 'allow' action for stateless ACLs. This patch makes to use
'allow' for stateless and 'allow-related' actions for stateful security
groups.

Limitation: There is currently an issue in core OVN that makes it not
possible to use statless ACL if a stateful ACL is present for port on
the same chassis.

NOTE: I don't know how to enable stateful-security-group API extension
so unittests are currently failing.

Blueprint: stateless-security-groups

Change-Id: I6f8ad1461cb3059aeb606b936296b8113538896e
Signed-off-by: Jakub Libosvar <libosvar@redhat.com>

[WIP] Add native OVSDB implementation for polling monitor

TODO: remove prints and extra logs for debugging
      UTs/FTs

This patch implements an OVS interface monitor based in the OVSDB
native implementation (OVSDB IDL, Open vSwitch Database Interface
Definition Language).

Closes-Bug: #1789592

commit_message:
Remove IPv6 hotplug test from the OVN jobs' blacklist

Root cause of this issue was fixed in the OVN:
https://mail.openvswitch.org/pipermail/ovs-dev/2020-June/371635.html
so we should be good to run this test in our gate now.

Change-Id: If5abde5f382a3da029974d617d3a49b3e690957f
Related-Bug: #1881558

commit_message:
Could not create subnet successful when gateway not in range of sunet cidr

When we create a subent, we need to provide the gateway address,
but if gateway not in range of subnet, we can still create subnet
successful, so this is not correct.

Fixes: bug #1884009
Change-Id: I8bb28f80614766b899860fb53020fc2d1f3956c6

commit_message:
[WIP] Fix the designate dns_name confilct for extra port

when the user try to add an extra port to already existing server
or create a server with multiple ports, designate will raise a
conflict exception in dns_name since it will be the same for the
two ports.

This also can solve the problem if the dns_name already exist
it will create another unique dns_name from the dns_name and
ip hash rather than failing to create a record

Change-Id: I1fb0cd0e1dc9466a50428b4a92b5dbbb97a524e0
Closes-Bug: #1879009

commit_message:
Ensure iptables rule was added only once

This patch adds a check for iptables_manager to ensure the rule
was added only once to the list. This will avoid some unexpected
behavior during rule removal procedure.

Change-Id: I352b0ff734682dfa8c3f95e938fd8455f720c674
Closes-Bug: #1845145

commit_message:
solve ingress packets causes flooding on integration bridge for vlan network

There is no need to add egress direct flows for vlan ports. For those ports,
traffic will still match the original NORMAL flow.

revisions:
[{'created': '2020-07-14 14:32:49.000000000', 'message': "quota: use native oslo.db retry

There are some issues with setting quota usages to dirty which cause
deadlocks that have been worked around by adding the global retry hook,
this has actually caused more issues in our larger scale deployments and
ended up giving retries without proper stacktraces and missing
savepoints.

All OpenStack projects adopt native use of oslo_db retry function
natively, the reason for the use of the current Neutron model is to
avoid nested retries, which really is a workaround rather than solving
the fundamental issue of clearing out the queries that deadlock.

This patch removes any retries from SELECT operations, as those will
likely not really be affected much (and don't need to be retried).  We
will be retrying the UPDATE operation anyways (if it's deadlocked on
that).

All of the update operations have been updated to use the oslo_db retry
decorator, we can probably drop some of those eventually (even a project
like Nova has very little of those (in ~250-ish database API functions,
only 13 are actually tagged to retry on deadlock).

It also removes the API-level retry for all operations, as it's much
better to hit and narrow down on the deadlock-able operations.  This
should eventually be moved onto all other components but for now, this
patch covers quota as it's a hard hit (plugging 250 ports concurrently
results in 504s and deadlocks everywhere).

Change-Id: Ibd3343fc74a9a78f3ec974c204a5bbf5310758b7
Related-Bug: #1777965
Related-Bug: #1771293
Related-Bug: #1887523

commit_message:
quota: use native oslo.db retry

There are some issues with setting quota usages to dirty which cause
deadlocks that have been worked around by adding the global retry hook,
this has actually caused more issues in our larger scale deployments and
ended up giving retries without proper stacktraces and missing
savepoints.

All OpenStack projects adopt native use of oslo_db retry function
natively, the reason for the use of the current Neutron model is to
avoid nested retries, which really is a workaround rather than solving
the fundamental issue of clearing out the queries that deadlock.

This patch removes any retries from SELECT operations, as those will
likely not really be affected much (and don't need to be retried).  We
will be retrying the UPDATE operation anyways (if it's deadlocked on
that).

All of the update operations have been updated to use the oslo_db retry
decorator, we can probably drop some of those eventually (even a project
like Nova has very little of those (in ~250-ish database API functions,
only 13 are actually tagged to retry on deadlock).

It also removes the API-level retry for all operations, as it's much
better to hit and narrow down on the deadlock-able operations.  This
should eventually be moved onto all other components but for now, this
patch covers quota as it's a hard hit (plugging 250 ports concurrently
results in 504s and deadlocks everywhere).

This patch also makes some changes to the quota driver to avoid having
calls for retries there as they are handled at a much lower level inside
the quota database API.

Change-Id: Ibd3343fc74a9a78f3ec974c204a5bbf5310758b7
Related-Bug: #1777965
Related-Bug: #1771293
Related-Bug: #1887523

commit_message:
[RFC] OVN: Add tool for offline migration of network type

__NOTE__: The purpose of this patch set is to gather initial
comments and feedback on the approach taken to solve the
described problem. Please refer to docstring in the added module
for more details.

The script needs to be updated to use common Neutron OVO existing
infrastructure for segment allocation, logging, configuration
parser etc. before it can be reviewed for possible inclusion in
the project.

I'd be happy to do that work if the gathered feedback points in a
direction of that being welcome, and any pointers for where to
enter the above described Neutron resources to do it properly
would also be welcome.

Change-Id: I2f7a9de24f079664892605a4de55666035537da3

commit_message:
Switch to uwsgi in grenade jobs

As we want to switch Neutron's default deployment method in Devstack
to be uwsgi, we need also to switch it in grenade jobs for both old and
new version. Otherwise, grenade jobs are failing as they can't update
from non-wsgi to wsgi deployment.

Change-Id: Ia4c7f62c64635d5a35d665c343478393d77e9ef7

commit_message:
[DNM] Make an attempt at have the gate trip lock contention

It would be useful if the gate caught problems like the one
described in LP: #1890432. Let's see if we can make it happen by
adjusting rally config or if there are other environmental
differences.

Change-Id: I1eb4c4aa160431bc4910d136fd7c08c5961fa0a7

commit_message:
Make changes to have a changeable port network id

The neutron-lib change I7cd0f76cbfc27f44923bba7a57839f3a5364c5d1
adds an extension to have a changable port network id when the
port has no fixed-ip address on it.

Change-Id: I346bd9fb99fe38caf7e7d804c62e1687e98e9c21

revisions:
[{'created': '2019-10-01 20:50:22.000000000', 'message': "[train][goal] Define new neutron-tempest-ipv6-only job

As part of Train community goal 'Support IPv6-Only Deployments and Testing'[1],
we need to define the integration job which deploy services
on IPv6 and perform testing to make sure service listen and communicate
over IPv6 properly.

Current 'tempest-ipv6-only' IPv6 job (running on neutron gate) only cover neutron
and run only smoke+ipv6 tests present in Tempest. But neutron-tempest-plugin has
more coverage for IPv6 and its stadium projects tests.

This commit adds the new job 'neutron-tempest-ipv6-only' which can deploy neutron
and other required services on IPv6 and run all required tests for Neutron and
its stadium projects IPv6 related tests.

After this, we can remove the tempest-ipv6-only from neutron gate and use this new
job instead.

commit_message:
[train][goal] Define new neutron-tempest-ipv6-only job

As part of Train community goal 'Support IPv6-Only Deployments and Testing'[1],
we need to define the integration job which deploy services
on IPv6 and perform testing to make sure service listen and communicate
over IPv6 properly.

Current 'tempest-ipv6-only' IPv6 job (running on neutron gate) only cover neutron
and run only smoke+ipv6 tests present in Tempest. But neutron-tempest-plugin has
more coverage for IPv6 and its stadium projects tests.

This commit adds the new job 'neutron-tempest-ipv6-only' which can deploy neutron
and other required services on IPv6 and run all required tests for Neutron and
its stadium projects IPv6 related tests.

After this, we can remove the tempest-ipv6-only from neutron gate and use this new
job instead.

Story: #2005477
Task: #35908

[1] https://governance.openstack.org/tc/goals/train/ipv6-support-and-testing.html

commit_message:
[WIP] Add cleanups for trunks

A new change in Neutron (see Needed-By) is tightening up how trunk ports
are tracked.  In order to avoid PortInUseAsTrunkParent errors in tests
that don't have cleanups for trunks, add them.

Change-Id: I6373d346f7b4a39f9fbe09c48b5a8e21ae8d08d6
Needed-By: https://review.opendev.org/717350

commit_message:
Optimize the way to define the api_extensions

Devstack now has a way to append the api_extensions to the
default extensiones defined in devstack side
- https://review.opendev.org/#/c/666508/

master devstack set the 'all' api extensions so master
job does not need to set the api extensions. 'all' means
here is every extensions will be considered as enabled.

stable branch devstack set default set of extensions for each
stable branch. Neutron stable jobs only needs to append
the additional api_extensions enabled in that stable
branch job.

Change-Id: I8912b1a123ac52c99b65b93884702e792fa7ea86

commit_message:
Ping external resource in the neutron tests

In patch [1] a new test, which tests connectivity from the VM to
the outside world was introduced.  This test is skipped by default,
unless "global_ip_address" will be set. So this patch sets
global_ip_address to be "zuul_site_mirror_fqdn", which is an external
host that should be reachable with great reliability.

[1] https://review.opendev.org/#/c/727764/

Depends-On: https://review.opendev.org/733952
Change-Id: I936fa45d0a5d102c80a72abe24c904917d67cd40

commit_message:
Change code to store and cleanup admin-created networks

The create_network() code always stores created networks
in cls.networks, which can lead to a failure deleting
them since they could have been created with the admin
client. For this reason, most callers using the admin
client add their own addCleanup() call.

Change callers to pass the admin client to create_network()
to properly store these networks in cls.networks so they
are cleaned automatically.

Removed cls.admin_networks from BaseNetworkTest class since
it is never used.

Change-Id: I9fdd666c91e38c115bc2f5ec17859711d869ba26

commit_message:
fix firewall group deletion occasionally failed in fwaas tests

Firewall group cannot be deleted when its status
is pending_update. Check whether the status of the
firewall group become to active or inactive before
deleting it.

Closes-Bug: #1889730
Change-Id: I3f0f2f7ef4e7bf616332f804f43501af08ac6acb

[{'created': '2020-04-20 10:47:52.000000000', 'message': "Improve QoS BW limit scenario tests

This patch improves qos scenario tests in cases when QoS policy is
attached to Neutron port and Floating IP.

In case when QoS is attached to the port, it changes values of bw
limits set. Before this patch limits where set first with lowest values
and later updated to some higher ones. But as our test is only checking
if real bandwidth is lower then configured one, such test can't catch
any issues with e.g. bandwidth limit rule updates.
So this patch changes this to set first highest value and then update
it to lower one.

In case when QoS is attached to Floating IP, it adds update of bandwidth
limit rule and ensure that this rule is also updated properly and new
limit is set for the Floating IP.

Change-Id: I58eb8bd6cf12287d98ae0c82b5f5aef576bd6df4

commit_message:
Improve QoS BW limit scenario tests

This patch improves qos scenario tests in cases when QoS policy is
attached to Neutron port and Floating IP.

In case when QoS is attached to the port, it changes values of bw
limits set. Before this patch limits where set first with lowest values
and later updated to some higher ones. But as our test is only checking
if real bandwidth is lower then configured one, such test can't catch
any issues with e.g. bandwidth limit rule updates.
So this patch changes this to set first highest value and then update
it to lower one.

In case when QoS is attached to Floating IP, it adds update of bandwidth
limit rule and ensure that this rule is also updated properly and new
limit is set for the Floating IP.

Change-Id: I58eb8bd6cf12287d98ae0c82b5f5aef576bd6df4

commit_message:
Add bindep.txt to fix unit tests

The unit tests fail since no mysqladmin command is installed, add
bindep.txt to install the needed binaries in our CI environment.

Add also the usual bindep tox environment for developers.

This commit includes the following unrelated changes
to pass the gate.
------------------------------------------------------------
Fix versions of neutron and friends

Change-Id: I0a98a0b39f9d39419dc81344423655fd03165648

Update sphinx requirements

commit_message:
Update master for stable/victoria

Add file to the reno documentation build to show release notes for
stable/victoria.

Use pbr instruction to increment the minor version number
automatically so that master versions are higher than the versions on
stable/victoria.

Change-Id: I09f54e58239b6c2e77f69bff07bc7fe72ce4690d
Sem-Ver: feature

commit_message:
(PoC)Classification field in Neutron DSCP

This patch is a PoC to demonstrate integration of
Neutron Classifier into Neutron QoS.
It extends the DSCP marking rule to accept an optional
arguement "classification_group_id" that creates a
unique pair with the "policy_id" so that multiple DSCP
marking rules can be added to a single policy so long
as the same policy and classification id are not
duplicated.

Change-Id: Ifd1c6409724e6c1f951ab5e3b103fc87ef31832e

commit_message:
Update TOX_CONSTRAINTS_FILE for stable/victoria

Update the URL to the upper-constraints file to point to the redirect
rule on releases.openstack.org so that anyone working on this branch
will switch to the correct upper-constraints list automatically when
the requirements repository branches.

Until the requirements repository has as stable/victoria branch, tests will
continue to use the upper-constraints list on master.

Change-Id: I7bc932a8b05492e17b97f9541005a6e806b9cc50

commit_message:
ovn migration: Fix neutron server container name

Previously docker command used grep to search for neutron server
container. It used image name instead of container name. With the switch
to podman, it stopped working. This patch fixes the container name.

Change-Id: Id650c2e7ac427dd53ebaab4e6d95d54efc657e3f
Closes-bug: #1895108
Signed-off-by: Jakub Libosvar <libosvar@redhat.com>
(cherry picked from commit 4b30dc2330423fd9fe68a70f7b2e0c6f925ecda4)

commit_message:
Disable dstat to enable tests on Ubuntu 20.04

Apparently dstat's bug causing it to show that kuryr-daemon is using
1 TB of RAM causes some buffer overflow in Python 3.8. We need to
disable it in order to enable testing on Ubuntu Focal.

Change-Id: Ifacc8c5f3e4a7adc010de75923d69f1df615450a

commit_message:
Fix setup.cfg keywords

author-email, home-page are aliases, replacing them for their final value

description-file -> long_description = file:

requires-python is old value and does not work, python-requires
is right metadata.

'python-requires' is introduced from PEP440 and requires-python was old value
in PEP345.
- https://packaging.python.org/guides/distributing-packages-using-setuptools/#python-requires
- https://www.python.org/dev/peps/pep-0345/#requires-python

Change-Id: I2d2cd5d660ef937bfe8445bae7cf6b279eb80b0f

commit_message:
Don't use ansible 2.10.0

It seems to have broken all jobs, let's not use it till we
fix those.

Also pin importlib-metadata 2.0.0 which is not compatible
with virtualenv 20.0.31.

Related-Bug: #1896738
Change-Id: I696605e312692b24059178b82446d947023f35d9

commit_message:
Update TOX_CONSTRAINTS_FILE for stable/victoria

Update the URL to the upper-constraints file to point to the redirect
rule on releases.openstack.org so that anyone working on this branch
will switch to the correct upper-constraints list automatically when
the requirements repository branches.

Until the requirements repository has as stable/victoria branch, tests will
continue to use the upper-constraints list on master.

Change-Id: I3b27b7fab319c7948dd01b4270d6ec6bf675db96

commit_message:
Document MD5 as the image checksum algo

This corrects the documentation, the checksum field maps to Ironic
instance_info.image_checksum which uses MD5, not SHA256.

See https://docs.openstack.org/ironic/latest/install/standalone.html#populating-instance-info

commit_message:
libvirt: make mdev types name attribute be optional

Some GPU drivers like i915 don't provide a name attribute for mdev types.
As we don't use this attribute yet, let's just make sure we support the fact
it's optional.

Change-Id: Ia745ed7095c74e2bfba38379e623a3f81e7799eb
Closes-Bug: #1896741

commit_message:
Replace deprecated auth_plugin by auth_type

The auth_plugin parameter was deprecated a while ago in keystoneauth
and should be replaced by auth_type. This patch updates the parameter
accordingly.

[1] https://github.com/openstack/keystoneauth/commit/a56ed4218aef5a2e528aa682cea967e767dca923

Change-Id: If8289993f494ebebdc125a71cc482b658acf4d51

commit_message:
Update master for stable/victoria

Add file to the reno documentation build to show release notes for
stable/victoria.

Use pbr instruction to increment the minor version number
automatically so that master versions are higher than the versions on
stable/victoria.

commit_message:
Fix keystone-startup.sh

keystone-startup.sh is using fernet_token_expiry instead of
fernet_key_rotation_interval - which effects in restart loop of keystone
containers - when restarted after 2-3 days.

Closes-Bug: #1895723

Change-Id: Ifff77af3d25d9dc659fff34f2ae3c6f2670df0f4

commit_message:
Check login in addtion to port reachability to make sure share server is available

When we start a share server,  we should make sure the server can be login
so that the later access to the server will success. Only check the port
reachable is not enough, especially when using private key to access a slow
share server, the immediately access after the port first available will fail.

Change-Id: I7bdc267eedaf3a43fcb6bfdecbb5863129a9ac5b
Closes-Bug: 1748139

commit_message:
Add OPENSTACK_ENDPOINT_TYPE to the connection

Pass interface to honor 'OPENSTACK_ENDPOINT_TYPE' so it can have multiple endpoints,
without this it only communicate with the public endpoint.

Closes-Bug: #1891230
Change-Id: I7caf9170d63eff388af5d690dd6b054188752381

TripleO CI uses 10.0.0.1 statically for the undercloud's
public interface. When using extra node in some job's
there is sometime a conflict, because the extra node get's

Adding support to define the allocation pools on the
public_net allows TripleO CI to define a pool with the
10.0.0.1 address eliminated.

A good practice would be to set up OVB to use
[{start: 10.0.0.128, end: 10.0.0.253}], and then configure
the undercloud/overcloud deployed on the OVB infrastructure
to use addresses in the range 10.0.0.1-10.0.0.127.

allocation pool setting, by default all addresses of the

commit_message:
Add allocation-pool support for the public_net

TripleO CI uses 10.0.0.1 statically for the undercloud's
public interface. When using extra node in some job's
there is sometime a conflict, because the extra node get's
the 10.0.0.1 address allocated.

Adding support to define the allocation pools on the
public_net allows TripleO CI to define a pool with the
10.0.0.1 address eliminated.

A good practice would be to set up OVB to use
[{start: 10.0.0.128, end: 10.0.0.253}], and then configure
the undercloud/overcloud deployed on the OVB infrastructure
to use addresses in the range 10.0.0.1-10.0.0.127.

The parameter public_net_allocation_pools controls the
allocation pool setting, by default all addresses of the
subnet is in the pool.

Related-Bug: #1874418
Change-Id: Ieca4864e069148abb49eb709bf7f48a14ef04e77
(cherry picked from commit ccec11f9c870a49909255b1d67f1f5042993de0e)

Fix type of public_net_allocation_pools

https://review.opendev.org/#/c/733598/ added support
of allocation_pools, but set type of public_net_allocation_pools
to comma_delimited_list which causes below issue because for
comma_delimited_list, list items are converted to string:-

Property error: : resources.public_subnet.properties.allocation_pools[0]:
"{'end': '10.0.0.199', 'start': '10.0.0.128'}" is not a map

We need to use type: json to get it work, this patch fixes it.

Related-Bug: #1874418
Change-Id: Iaebb297e5018ce8db6dd1f67a308e7707117fe03
(cherry picked from commit ff4d8fa4e27622ef2b08db10f8d7eafaa397166a)

commit_message:
Update TOX_CONSTRAINTS_FILE for stable/victoria

Update the URL to the upper-constraints file to point to the redirect
rule on releases.openstack.org so that anyone working on this branch
will switch to the correct upper-constraints list automatically when
the requirements repository branches.

Until the requirements repository has as stable/victoria branch, tests will
continue to use the upper-constraints list on master.

Change-Id: Ie7836671e746b143b3f1fb91af1111df4945c8e4

Update TOX_CONSTRAINTS_FILE for stable/victoria

Update the URL to the upper-constraints file to point to the redirect
rule on releases.openstack.org so that anyone working on this branch
will switch to the correct upper-constraints list automatically when
the requirements repository branches.

Until the requirements repository has as stable/victoria branch, tests will
continue to use the upper-constraints list on master.

Change-Id: I4c80011b0a68e6a950356bd0d2570868df3d80ea

commit_message:
Update TOX_CONSTRAINTS_FILE for stable/victoria

Update the URL to the upper-constraints file to point to the redirect
rule on releases.openstack.org so that anyone working on this branch
will switch to the correct upper-constraints list automatically when
the requirements repository branches.

Until the requirements repository has as stable/victoria branch, tests will
continue to use the upper-constraints list on master.

Change-Id: I73b04d5639ceccb4880f48445f921912792fa5be

By default, the overcloud plan name is "overcloud" but it can be renamed

'}]
commit_message:
enable-ssh-admin: allow to override plan name

By default, the overcloud plan name is "overcloud" but it can be renamed
if the stack is named directly. Allowing the operator to override it so
they can run that script on a deployment where the stack is named
differently than the default.

Change-Id: I05029d30447592d4e16d85acc490cda69b101e9c
Closes-Bug: #1896505

commit_message:
Add Access Rules tests

Access rules for application credentials were added in the Train release
of keystone. This change adds related CRUD tests for access rules. See
the API reference for additional information[1].

[1] https://docs.openstack.org/api-ref/identity/v3/index.html#application-credentials

Change-Id: Ifd4ff2245277c2c57f5ccf450923434c0277a724

commit_message:
Add openstack overcloud export ceph

Add a new command to export Ceph information from one or
more Heat stacks to be used as input of another stack.
Creates a valid YAML file with the CephExternalMultiConfig
parameter populated.

Also have export's export_password use yaml.safe_load in
place of the deprecated yaml.load.

Closes-Bug: #1895034
Change-Id: Ibdf9115e92c6b476b99d6df785b0c7e9f23991de

commit_message:
Proposing victoria RC1 for mistral

As a courtesy for project teams, on RC1 week the release management
team proposes a RC1 release for all cycle-with-rc deliverables,
based on HEAD. That RC1 will double as the branch point for the
stable/victoria branch for mistral.

Release liaison or PTL should +1 this proposal if they are happy
with it, amend this proposal (for example with a more recent SHA)
to match their needs, or -1 to block it until release-critical
issues are all fixed.

Change-Id: Ib411d6cda54f6b09cab3e47bd6a4734a5dbe6818
Signed-off-by: Thierry Carrez <thierry@openstack.org>

commit_message:
Implementation CNF with VNFM and CISM in Tacker

Implements: blueprint cnf-support-with-etsi-nfv-specs

The CNF instantiation/termination
* Load CNF definition files in CSAR artifact
* Extend Kubernetes infra_driver for general APIs

Other modify
* update lower-constraints.txt and requirments.txt to
  satisfy our k8s client usage
  (kubernets:6.0.0->11.0.0, urllib3:1.22.0->1.24.2)

Change-Id: I20ffbaec14ac5fb8236bd61416c2604b7a6590f6

[{'created': '2020-09-11 21:12:57.000000000', 'message': 'Add support for encrypting Ironic API

This patch introduces an optional backend encryption for the Ironic API
and Ironic Inspector service. When used in conjunction with enabling
TLS for service API endpoints, network communcation will be encrypted
end to end, from client through HAProxy to the Ironic service.

commit_message:
Add support for encrypting Ironic API

This patch introduces an optional backend encryption for the Ironic API
service. When used in conjunction with enabling TLS for service API
endpoints, network communcation will be encrypted end to end, from
client through HAProxy to the Ironic service.

Change-Id: I9edf7545c174ca8839ceaef877bb09f49ef2b451
Partially-Implements: blueprint add-ssl-internal-network

commit_message:
Updated the weights section of Compute schedulers in nova

Description: Mentioning cells in here is not qualified as only
for cells v1, which is deprecated. So, removed them to avoid
confusion. The "Host weighting options" section lists several
options with their now deprecated config option group: replaced
the table with descriptions to a list of related options, so
there is context. Linked the url
https://docs.openstack.org/nova/rocky/user/filter-scheduler.html#weights
which actually explains the various in-tree weighers.

Change-Id: Ie81e9dc72dd254127f7ed9d974fab886dc2ee8a2
Closes-Bug: #1805233

'}, {'created': '2020-09-16 12:29:26.000000000', 'message': 'Add support for custom logging file defined by user

Kolla-ansible deployment currently using default logging
behaviour from openstack.

This patch is adding support for custom logging defined by
user. This is very useful for users who wants to customize
logging options (for each service separately).

As an example, you can imagine that user wants to send
logs as JSON natively via python3-fluent-logger directly to some IP.
This can be now achieved by custom logging.conf defined
in /etc/kolla/config/{service_name}/logging.conf by user.

Change-Id: I0dd0834ab5872006a1402b2ebf7fd09d8f62fddc
Closes-Bug: #1842317
'}, {'created': '2020-09-17 09:15:33.000000000', 'message': 'Add support for custom logging file defined by user

behaviour from openstack.

user. This is very useful for users who wants to customize

As an example, you can imagine that user wants to send
logs as JSON natively via python3-fluent-logger directly to some IP.
This can be now achieved by custom logging.conf defined
in /etc/kolla/config/{service_name}/logging.conf by user.

commit_message:
Add support for custom logging file defined by user

Kolla-ansible deployment currently using default logging
behaviour from openstack.

This patch is adding support for custom logging defined by
user. This is very useful for users who wants to customize
logging options (for each service separately).

As an example, you can imagine that user wants to send
logs as JSON natively via python3-fluent-logger directly to some IP.
This can be now achieved by custom logging.conf defined
in /etc/kolla/config/{service_name}/logging.conf by user.

Change-Id: I0dd0834ab5872006a1402b2ebf7fd09d8f62fddc
Closes-Bug: #1842317

commit_message:
Fix CA file for nova client

If a custom CA file is configured via nova_ca_certificates_file,
currently communication with Keystone will fail, since the session is
not created using this CA file. The same is true for nova_api_insecure.

This change fixes the issue by using a keystoneauth session loader.

Closes-Bug: #1873736

Change-Id: I54a4f398a06c61e0f6f8f3efd3e4b6214bca756b
(cherry picked from commit 3bd82c776c91bdd1caee474f3fc9cda18927da7f)

commit_message:
DevStack: Disable leader election for K8s services

The DevStack plugin is really designed just for gate testing and
developer usage. In both use cases normally we won't run K8s services on
multiple nodes. Because of that this commit disables leader election for
kube-scheduler and kube-controller-manager. The motivation behind this
is that on the OpenInfra gate VMs we often see degraded storage
performance that affects etcd. If that happens during leader-election of
a service, it'll crash, leaving us with broken and unrecoverable K8s.
This should eliminate the issue.

Change-Id: Ib84ed289c9aaf3ae27af1c7ffa8aab2f8ba48671
(cherry picked from commit acfe74957442eabcb2922493ade37c5eadf98cf7)

commit_message:
Update TOX_CONSTRAINTS_FILE for stable/victoria

Update the URL to the upper-constraints file to point to the redirect
rule on releases.openstack.org so that anyone working on this branch
will switch to the correct upper-constraints list automatically when
the requirements repository branches.

Until the requirements repository has as stable/victoria branch, tests will
continue to use the upper-constraints list on master.

Change-Id: Ib8b356afe30146b920a38a9de023fd417c2073c4

commit_message:
Update master for stable/victoria

Add file to the reno documentation build to show release notes for
stable/victoria.

Use pbr instruction to increment the minor version number
automatically so that master versions are higher than the versions on
stable/victoria.

Sem-Ver: feature

commit_message:
Remove error code 412 support for updating VNF

Because there is no API request/response specification for Etag
in ETSI NFV SOL documentation, we would like to remove the
support of `error code: 412 Precondition Failed` for updating
VNF operation.

Change-Id: I5d08b32ab09b08f64cf47b9dc1df02e82ffff0e8

revisions:
[{'created': '2020-09-25 08:36:25.000000000', 'message': 'Update TOX_CONSTRAINTS_FILE for stable/victoria

Update the URL to the upper-constraints file to point to the redirect
rule on releases.openstack.org so that anyone working on this branch
will switch to the correct upper-constraints list automatically when
the requirements repository branches.

Until the requirements repository has as stable/victoria branch, tests will
continue to use the upper-constraints list on master.

Change-Id: I8bb45867250179ca6604eb9f50f4df3d9dc2c879
'}]
commit_message:
Update TOX_CONSTRAINTS_FILE for stable/victoria

Update the URL to the upper-constraints file to point to the redirect
rule on releases.openstack.org so that anyone working on this branch
will switch to the correct upper-constraints list automatically when
the requirements repository branches.

Until the requirements repository has as stable/victoria branch, tests will
continue to use the upper-constraints list on master.

Change-Id: I8bb45867250179ca6604eb9f50f4df3d9dc2c879

'}, {'created': '2020-06-04 13:27:05.000000000', 'message': 'Output correct json for security groups in 'openstack server show'

Fixes incorrect json output for 'openstack server show -f json'.
The security group json output groups all the json as one
for e.g. "security_groups": "name='group1'\nname='group2'"
The correct output should be
"security_groups" : [{"name" : "group1"}, {"name" : "group2"}]

Story: 2007755

Change-Id: I1b1cac716329e0530400aff782c08000b21d8e1d

commit_message:
Output correct json for security groups in 'openstack server show'

Fixes incorrect json output for 'openstack server show -f json'.
The security group json output groups all the json as one
for e.g. "security_groups": "name='group1'\nname='group2'"
The correct output should be
"security_groups" : [{"name" : "group1"}, {"name" : "group2"}]
properties and volumes_attached fields also has similar issue.

Story: 2007755

Change-Id: I1b1cac716329e0530400aff782c08000b21d8e1d

commit_message:
Update TOX_CONSTRAINTS_FILE for stable/victoria

Update the URL to the upper-constraints file to point to the redirect
rule on releases.openstack.org so that anyone working on this branch
will switch to the correct upper-constraints list automatically when
the requirements repository branches.

Until the requirements repository has as stable/victoria branch, tests will
continue to use the upper-constraints list on master.

Change-Id: If9946c3dd78752eaa3548de0cec45517a043e7bc

commit_message:
Make message parsing more resilient

Firmware from some vendors only includes the MessageKey in the
MessageID. In this case, fall back to finding the MessageKey first in
the Messages MessageRegistryFile and then in the BaseMessages
MessageRegistryFile.

If the message can't be found, then set the parsed message to 'unknown'
instead of throwing an exception.

If there are not enough arguments to populate the message, then
populate the missing arguments with 'unknown'.

Change-Id: I045f82167a415c92d6b67532222aef89ab1d68ef
(cherry picked from commit bad68e1e60ba2ea561e36394d1176e2315e3a907)

commit_message:
Proposing victoria RC1 for octavia-dashboard

As a courtesy for project teams, on RC1 week the release management
team proposes a RC1 release for all cycle-with-rc deliverables,
based on HEAD. That RC1 will double as the branch point for the
stable/victoria branch for octavia-dashboard.

Release liaison or PTL should +1 this proposal if they are happy
with it, amend this proposal (for example with a more recent SHA)
to match their needs, or -1 to block it until release-critical
issues are all fixed.

Change-Id: Ia7b017bdab9192f23a47f9fbc13f6a38c2bb851f
Signed-off-by: Thierry Carrez <thierry@openstack.org>

commit_message:
Proposing victoria RC1 for octavia

As a courtesy for project teams, on RC1 week the release management
team proposes a RC1 release for all cycle-with-rc deliverables,
based on HEAD. That RC1 will double as the branch point for the
stable/victoria branch for octavia.

Release liaison or PTL should +1 this proposal if they are happy
with it, amend this proposal (for example with a more recent SHA)
to match their needs, or -1 to block it until release-critical
issues are all fixed.

Change-Id: I955071861696960cb7f1d2edcee495749aa7e0f8
Signed-off-by: Thierry Carrez <thierry@openstack.org>

commit_message:
Proposing victoria RC1 for senlin

As a courtesy for project teams, on RC1 week the release management
team proposes a RC1 release for all cycle-with-rc deliverables,
based on HEAD. That RC1 will double as the branch point for the
stable/victoria branch for senlin.

Release liaison or PTL should +1 this proposal if they are happy
with it, amend this proposal (for example with a more recent SHA)
to match their needs, or -1 to block it until release-critical
issues are all fixed.

Change-Id: I3c59eb2010c80da18850b4e1196095750a87db73
Signed-off-by: Thierry Carrez <thierry@openstack.org>
